var definitions = ['<h2>Ich bin dort gewesen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>bin</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". However, when used with a past participle as it is in this sentence, it helps to form the present perfect tense, which is used to describe an action that has been completed in the past.</div><div><strong>dort</strong> This is an adverb in German, meaning "there" in English. It indicates the location in relation to the speaker, similar to how "there" is used in English.</div><div><strong>gewesen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "sein", or "to be" in English. When combined with "bin" as mentioned earlier, it forms the present perfect tense, which in this context can indicate a state of having been somewhere in the past.</div>','<h2>Wir werden uns dort treffen.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werden</strong> This is a modal verb used to form the future tense in German, and it can be translated as "will" in English. It’s used here to indicate a future action.</div><div><strong>uns</strong> This is the accusative and dative reflexive pronoun for the first-person plural in German, equivalent to "ourselves" in English. It indicates that the action of the verb is reflected back onto the subject.</div><div><strong>dort</strong> This is an adverb meaning "there" in English. It specifies the location where the action of the verb is taking place.</div><div><strong>treffen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb meaning "to meet" in English. It indicates the action that the subject will perform.</div>','<h2>Mensch! Dieses Steak ist gar nicht schlecht!</h2><div><strong>Mensch!</strong> This is an interjection used in German to express surprise or emphasis, similar to "wow" or "man" in English.</div><div><strong>Dieses</strong> This is the neuter nominative or accusative singular form of the demonstrative pronoun "dieser", which means "this" in English. It points out a specific object that is close to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Steak</strong> This is a loanword from English, used in German with the same meaning. It refers to a cut of meat typically grilled or fried.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject "Steak" with the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>gar nicht</strong> This phrase is made up of the word "gar", which serves to intensify the negation, and "nicht", which means "not" in English. Together, they strongly negate the statement that follows.</div><div><strong>schlecht!</strong> This is an adjective meaning "bad" in English. In this context, the phrase "gar nicht schlecht" is used to express that something is surprisingly good, similar to saying "not bad at all" or "actually quite good" in English.</div>','<h2>Ich habe gar keine Idee.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It indicates possession or, in this case, a state of mind.</div><div><strong>gar</strong> This is an adverb meaning "at all" or "absolutely" in English. It is often used for emphasis in negations.</div><div><strong>keine</strong> This is a negative indefinite article in German, equivalent to "no" or "not any" in English. It negates the noun that follows.</div><div><strong>Idee</strong> This is a noun meaning "idea" in German. It’s the object of the sentence that is being negated by "keine".</div>','<h2>Es wird heiß hier drinnen!</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the German third-person neutral pronoun "es", equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wird</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "werden", which means "to become". It indicates a change of state or a future state.</div><div><strong>heiß</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "hot". In this sentence, it is used in the predicate to describe the change of state.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This word means "here" in English. It’s an adverb describing the location.</div><div><strong>drinnen</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "inside". It specifies the location referred to by "hier", indicating that it is getting hot inside rather than outside.</div>','<h2>Die Polizeistation ist nicht weit von hier.</h2><div><strong>Die</strong> This is the German definite article for feminine, nominative singular noun or the plural for all genders, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes a feminine singular noun in the nominative case here.</div><div><strong>Polizeistation</strong> This is a compound German noun, consisting of "Polizei" (police) and "Station" (station). It means "police station" and is feminine, which is why it is preceded by "die". It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It indicates existence or a state of being.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is a German adverb and negation particle that translates to "not" in English. It negates the following adjective "weit" (far).</div><div><strong>weit</strong> This is a German adjective which means "far" when describing distance. It’s used here in the positive form to describe the proximity of the police station.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a German preposition which usually means "from" or "of", indicating spatial relations. It’s used here in conjunction with "hier" to describe the location of the police station relative to the speaker’s current position.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "here". It specifies the reference point for the location being described.</div>','<h2>Kinder! Geht jetzt schlafen! Ich will nicht einen Ton hören!</h2><div><strong>Kinder</strong> This is the plural form of the German word for "child", referring to "children". It is being used here as a form of address to get the attention of the children.</div><div><strong>Geht</strong> This is the imperative form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go" or "to walk". In this context, it means "go" and is a command directed at the children.</div><div><strong>jetzt</strong> This translates to "now" in English, indicating the immediacy of the command.</div><div><strong>schlafen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to sleep". Coupled with "geht", it forms the command "go to sleep".</div><div><strong>Ich</strong> This denotes the first-person singular pronoun "I" in English, indicating the speaker of the sentence.</div><div><strong>will</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "wollen", which means "to want". In this case, it is used to express the speaker’s desire or demand.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This translates to "not" in English and is used to negate a verb, action, or statement.</div><div><strong>einen Ton</strong> This phrase means "a sound" in English, with "einen" being the accusative masculine singular indefinite article for the noun "Ton", indicating a single sound.</div><div><strong>hören</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to hear". The sentence ends indicating that the speaker does not want to hear a single sound, with the phrase "Ich will nicht einen Ton hören" translating as "I do not want to hear a sound".</div>','<h2>Ich hörte, dass du ausgezogen bist? Wo wohnst du jetzt?</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the first sentence.</div><div><strong>hörte</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "hören", which means "to hear". Here, it refers to the speaker having heard some information.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German that means "that". It’s used to introduce a subordinate clause</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>ausgezogen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "ausziehen", which means "to move out". The construction "bist ausgezogen" (with "bist" being the auxiliary verb) forms the present perfect tense, which is used here to express a completed action in the speaker’s past.</div><div><strong>bist?</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". Here, combined with "ausgezogen" it forms a present perfect tense construction. It also turns the statement into a question due to the question mark.</div><div><strong>Wo</strong> This is the adverb "where" in German, used to ask about a location.</div><div><strong>wohnst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "wohnen", which means "to live" or "to reside".</div><div><strong>du</strong> The pronoun is repeated since German often allows splitting the subject pronoun and its verb for clarity or emphasis, especially in questions.</div><div><strong>jetzt?</strong> This is the adverb "now" in German, asking for the current state or location.</div>','<h2>Deutsch ist nicht immer einfach zu lernen, aber es ist eine wunderschöne Sprache.</h2><div><strong>Deutsch</strong> This is the German word for "German". It refers to the German language in this context. It’s being used as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It is used here to describe the state of the German language being the subject.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German word for "not". It negates the statement that follows, implying that learning German is not always something.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> The German adverb meaning "always". It often describes the frequency of an action or state.</div><div><strong>einfach</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "easy". When used with "nicht immer", it negates the notion of German being always easy to learn.</div><div><strong>zu lernen</strong> This is an infinitive phrase combining "zu" (to) with "lernen" (learn), meaning "to learn". It’s a common construction in German to describe actions.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This word translates to "but" in English. It’s a conjunction used to introduce a contrast or exception.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. In this sentence, "es" refers to the German language.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> Again, this is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", meaning "to be". It’s used here for the second time in the sentence to describe the state of the German language.</div><div><strong>eine</strong> This is the indefinite article in German for feminine or plural nouns in the nominative or accusative case. It translates to "a" or "an" in English. Here it precedes "wunderschöne", a feminine adjective, which in turn precedes the feminine noun "Sprache".</div><div><strong>wunderschöne</strong> This is a German adjective that means "beautiful", "wonderful", or "gorgeous". When preceding a feminine noun like "Sprache", it takes an -e ending.</div><div><strong>Sprache</strong> This is the German word for "language". It is a feminine noun, in the nominative case, and the main object of the second clause of the sentence.</div>','<h2>Man muss immer Respekt vor Älteren haben.</h2><div><strong>Man</strong> This is the German impersonal pronoun often used to mean "one", "you", or "people" in general. It is used to make general statements.</div><div><strong>muss</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "müssen", which means "must" or "have to". It expresses necessity or obligation.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is an adverb meaning "always" in English. It is used to indicate that the action is to be done at all times.</div><div><strong>Respekt</strong> This is a masculine noun meaning "respect" in English. In German, nouns are capitalized and "der Respekt" is the singular nominative form.</div><div><strong>vor</strong> This is a preposition that can mean "before" or "in front of", but in this context, it means "toward" as in showing respect "toward" someone.</div><div><strong>Älteren</strong> This is the comparative form of "alt" (old), used here as a noun meaning "elderly people" or "elders". In German, adjectives used as nouns are capitalized, and the "den" ending denotes the plural dative case due to the preposition "vor".</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb which means "to have" in English. It is part of the verb phrase "muss ... haben" (must have) and is used here to indicate what one must have towards the elderly — respect.</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Und was genau machst du dort?</h2><div><strong>Und</strong> This is the German word for "and". It’s often used to connect sentences or phrases.</div><div><strong>was</strong> This is the German interrogative pronoun meaning "what". It’s used to ask for specific information.</div><div><strong>genau</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "exactly". It’s used here to ask for precise information.</div><div><strong>machst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the German verb "machen", which means "to do" or "to make". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>dort?</strong> This is the German adverb meaning "there". It indicates the place where the action is being performed and is used here in the context of a question.</div>','<h2>Jenes Pferd. Das Pferd dort.</h2><div><strong>Jenes</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German used to indicate a specific object that is further away from the speaker. It could be translated to "that" or "yonder" in English and is similar to "dieses" (this) but used for objects that are more distant.</div><div><strong>Pferd.</strong> This is the German word for "horse". It is a neutral noun in the singular nominative case.</div><div><strong>Das</strong> This is a definite article in German for the neutral gender in the nominative case. It can be translated as "the" in English.</div><div><strong>pferd</strong> This word is the same as earlier, it means "horse". Repeated here as part of the second sentence.</div><div><strong>dort.</strong> This is an adverb in German meaning "there". It indicates the location of the horse mentioned in the second sentence, implying some distance from the speaker but perhaps visible.</div>','<h2>Jene Affen. Die Affen dort.</h2><div><strong>Jene</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German used to refer to something that is further away in place or time, similar to the English "those". It is used to point to a specific group of things or people that are not close to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Affen</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Affe", which means "monkey" or "ape" in English. It refers to the animals being discussed, in this case, monkeys or apes.</div><div><strong>Die</strong> This word is a definite article in German used for plural nouns, and it’s the equivalent of the English "the". It operates to specify the noun it precedes, indicating that the speaker is talking about a particular group of things or people.</div><div><strong>dort</strong> This translates to "there" in English. It indicates a specific location that is away from both the speaker and the listener. It gives a sense of direction or position related to the noun that comes before it—the apes, in this case.</div>','<h2>Was ist mit denen dort drüben in diesem Kasten?</h2><div><strong>Was</strong> This is the German interrogative pronoun for "what". It indicates that a question is being asked.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It describes the existence or a state of being.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a German preposition that translates to "with" in English. It is used to indicate accompaniment, involvement, or possession.</div><div><strong>denen</strong> This is the demonstrative pronoun in the dative plural, corresponding to "those" in English. It refers to people or objects that are at a distance from the speaker.</div><div><strong>dort</strong> This translates to "there" in English, indicating a place or location.</div><div><strong>drüben</strong> Another locational term that means "over there" in English, often used to refer to a place that is on the opposite side or is some distance away.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This preposition in German is used similarly to English, meaning "in".</div><div><strong>diesem</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in the dative singular neuter form, meaning "this". It refers to something close to the speaker, with "Kasten" being the particular object in this case.</div><div><strong>Kasten</strong> This is a masculine noun meaning "box" or "case" in English. It references a physical object that can contain other objects.</div>','<h2>Willkommen in meiner Welt. Welche Position hast du dort?</h2><div><strong>Willkommen</strong> This is the German word for "welcome". It is used here to greet someone into one’s own space or sphere.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a German preposition that translates to "in" in English. It indicates the location where the welcome is occurring.</div><div><strong>meiner</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "mein" in the dative case, combined with the feminine singular ending "-er", which translates to "my" in English and refers to ownership of the world by the speaker.</div><div><strong>Welt</strong> This is the German noun for "world" used in the singular form. It signifies the place or environment that the speaker is welcoming someone into.</div><div><strong>Welche</strong> This is the interrogative pronoun "which" or "what kind" in German. It is used here to ask about the type or nature of something, specifically the position the other person holds.</div><div><strong>Position</strong> This is the German word for "position" or "role". It refers to a job title, status, or function someone has in a particular context or world.</div><div><strong>hast</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the German verb "haben", which means "to have". It indicates possession or having something, in this case asking about the role or position one holds.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the personal pronoun for the second-person singular "you" in German. It is the subject of the sentence, indicating the person being asked about their position.</div><div><strong>dort?</strong> This is the German adverb for "there". It refers to the place previously mentioned, in this case, the speaker’s "world". It’s used at the end of the question to specify the location relating to the position being asked about.</div>','<h2>Nein, die Schule ist toll. Ich mache meine Sache dort ziemlich gut.</h2><div><strong>Nein</strong> This is the German word for "no". It negates a statement or responds negatively to a question.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This is the definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s used here in the feminine nominative case along with a feminine noun.</div><div><strong>Schule</strong> This is a feminine noun in German meaning "school". It is the subject of the sentence and takes the nominative case after the definite article.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It links the subject "die Schule" with the adjective "toll".</div><div><strong>toll</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "great" or "fantastic". It describes the noun "Schule".</div><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the second sentence.</div><div><strong>mache</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "machen", which means "to do". It indicates an action performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>meine</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "my" in English. It’s in the accusative case, feminine or plural, and denotes ownership or relation to the noun "Sache".</div><div><strong>Sache</strong> This is a feminine noun in German meaning "thing" or "matter". It’s the direct object of the verb "mache" in the accusative case.</div><div><strong>dort</strong> This is an adverb in German meaning "there". It indicates location and relates to where the action of doing well is occurring.</div><div><strong>ziemlich</strong> This is an adverb meaning "quite" or "fairly". It modifies the adjective "gut" to describe the extent of how well the action is performed.</div><div><strong>gut</strong> This is an adjective meaning "good". It is used here to describe how the speaker is doing in school.</div>','<h2>Ja, es ist sehr schön hier.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It confirms a statement or responds affirmatively to a question.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or existence of the subject.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "very". It’s used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>schön</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "beautiful" or "nice". Here, it describes the place being talked about.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "here". It indicates the location being referred to in this statement.</div>','<h2>Sind Sie schon lange hier?</h2><div><strong>Sind</strong> This is the second-person plural present indicative form of "sein", the German verb "to be". It also serves as the formal second-person singular, equivalent to "are" in English.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. In this context, it addresses the listener formally.</div><div><strong>schon</strong> This is an adverb that can mean "already" or "yet" in English. In this question, it implies a sense of the time that has passed.</div><div><strong>lange</strong> This is an adjective meaning "long" in English, referring here to the duration of time.</div><div><strong>hier?</strong> This is an adverb meaning "here" in English. It indicates the location being referred to in the question.</div>','<h2>Hier ist der Umkleideraum.</h2><div><strong>Hier</strong> This is the German adverb for "here". It indicates the location or place where the speaker is referring to.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It denotes existence or a state of being.</div><div><strong>der</strong> This is the masculine singular definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It is used here to specify the particular noun that follows.</div><div><strong>Umkleideraum</strong> This is a compound noun in German. "Umkleide" means "changing" and "Raum" means "room", thus "Umkleideraum" translates to "changing room" or "locker room" in English. This is the subject of the sentence and indicates a room designated for changing clothes, typically found in sports facilities, pools, or shops.</div>','<h2>Es regnet selten hier.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the German pronoun for "it", typically used as a subject for general statements or for the weather.</div><div><strong>regnet</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "regnen", which means "to rain". It indicates the action of precipitation in the present moment.</div><div><strong>selten</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "rarely" or "seldom". It modifies the verb and indicates the frequency of the action.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is the German adverb meaning "here". It specifies the location where the action is taking place.</div>','<h2>Ist das Wasser hier rein?</h2><div><strong>Ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense of the German verb "sein", which means "to be". It’s used here to form a question.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is the neutral definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s used here to refer to "water" which is a neuter noun in German.</div><div><strong>Wasser</strong> This is the German word for "water". It’s a neuter noun in nominative case since it’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is the German adverb for "here", indicating location.</div><div><strong>rein</strong> This is a German adjective that means "clean" or "pure". Here, it’s used as a predicative adjective, meaning it describes the subject "Wasser" and is linked by the verb "ist".</div>','<h2>Ach was! Ist das weit von hier?</h2><div><strong>Ach</strong> This is an interjection in German, often used to express disbelief or mild surprise. It is similar to "oh" or "ah" in English.</div><div><strong>was</strong> This is the German word for "what". But in this interjection, it doesn’t necessarily keep its literal meaning. Instead, it often reflects a reaction, such as "really?" or "seriously?" when expressing doubt or surprise.</div><div><strong>Ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be".</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is the neuter singular definite article "the" or a demonstrative pronoun "that", depending on context. In this sentence, it acts as a demonstrative pronoun referring to something previously mentioned or understood from the context.</div><div><strong>weit</strong> This is the German word for "far". It’s an adjective used to describe distance.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a preposition in German that can mean "from" or "of".</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is the German word for "here". It refers to the current location of the speaker or the context within the conversation.</div>','<h2>Danke, hier ist Ihr Wechselgeld.</h2><div><strong>Danke</strong> This is the German word for "thanks" or "thank you". It’s an expression of gratitude.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is the German adverb for "here". It indicates the place or position of something.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It’s used to state the existence or presence of something.</div><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This word is the formal second-person possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "your" in English. It shows ownership or association with the person being addressed formally.</div><div><strong>Wechselgeld</strong> This is a German noun meaning "change" (as in the money given back when a larger amount is used for a smaller payment). It is a compound word, with "Wechsel" meaning "exchange" or "change" and "Geld" meaning "money".</div>','<h2>Würdest du hier leben wollen?</h2><div><strong>Würdest</strong> This is the second-person singular conditional form of the verb "würden", the conditional mood of "werden", which means "would". It indicates a hypothetical or polite request.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is an adverb meaning "here". It specifies the location being referred to in the sentence.</div><div><strong>leben</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb that means "to live". It’s the main verb in this sentence, used in its base form.</div><div><strong>wollen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the modal verb "wollen" meaning "to want". Here, it expresses the desire or intention associated with the main verb "leben".</div>','<h2>Danke. Und hier ist die Küche.</h2><div><strong>Danke</strong> This is the German word for "thanks" or "thank you". It is used to express gratitude.</div><div><strong>Und</strong> This is the German conjunction for "and". It is used to connect words or phrases in a sentence.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is the German adverb for "here". It indicates the location or place being referred to in the context of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It describes the state of being, existence or location.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This is the feminine singular nominative definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes the feminine noun "Küche".</div><div><strong>Küche</strong> This is the German word for "kitchen". It is a feminine noun referring to the room where food is prepared and cooked.</div>','<h2>Nein, es ist ziemlich nah von hier.</h2><div><strong>Nein</strong> This is the German word for "no". It negates a statement or responds negatively to a question.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person neutral pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>ziemlich</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "quite" or "rather". It’s used here to modify the adjective that follows it, indicating a degree of closeness.</div><div><strong>nah</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "close" or "near". It describes proximity.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is the German preposition that translates to "from" in English. It’s used to indicate the point of origin or a standard of comparison.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "here". It indicates a place or location, referring to the current position or situation.</div>','<h2>Sie müssen jetzt arbeiten.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German pronoun for "they" or the formal "you". In this sentence, it’s used as the subject and the context determines whether it refers to "they" or "you" in the formal sense.</div><div><strong>müssen</strong> This is the conjugated form of the modal verb "müssen" which means "must" or "have to". It implies necessity or obligation and is used here in the plural form or the formal (singular or plural) "you".</div><div><strong>jetzt</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "now". It indicates the time when the action is supposed to take place.</div><div><strong>arbeiten</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb meaning "to work". In this sentence, it is used in combination with the modal verb "müssen" to express the necessity to work.</div>','<h2>Ist es für jetzt oder später?</h2><div><strong>Ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It’s equivalent to "is" in English and is used here as the helping verb in the question.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>für</strong> This is a preposition in German that means "for" in English. It indicates the purpose or time for something.</div><div><strong>jetzt</strong> This is an adverb in German meaning "now" in English. It refers to the current moment or the immediate time.</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is a conjunction in German meaning "or" in English. It is used to offer a choice or alternative between two options.</div><div><strong>später</strong> This is an adverb in German that means "later" in English. It indicates a time that is to come in the future.</div><div>The sentence as a whole, "Ist es für jetzt oder später?" translates to "Is it for now or for later?" and is typically used when asking if something is meant to occur immediately or at a later time.</div>','<h2>Nein, ich bin jetzt Krankenschwester.</h2><div><strong>Nein</strong> This is the German word for "no". It negates a statement or responds negatively to a question.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>bin</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>jetzt</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "now". It specifies the timing of the state of being expressed in the sentence.</div><div><strong>Krankenschwester</strong> This is a German noun meaning "nurse". It refers to a female healthcare professional. The profession is being used here to denote the speaker’s current occupation. If the nurse were male, the word would be "Krankenpfleger".</div>','<h2>Für jetzt, baldmöglichst bitte.</h2><div><strong>Für</strong> This is the German preposition for "for". It indicates the object or person that is the recipient or beneficiary of an action or state. In this context, it relates to a time frame.</div><div><strong>jetzt</strong> This is the German adverb for "now". It refers to the present moment or the current time.</div><div><strong>baldmöglichst</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "as soon as possible". It’s used to express urgency or a desire for something to happen very soon.</div><div><strong>bitte</strong> This is the German word for "please". It’s a polite addition to requests or questions, indicating courtesy.</div>','<h2>Ja, und wie hoch ist mein Saldo jetzt?</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It’s used to confirm, agree, or acknowledge a statement or question.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect words, phrases, or clauses.</div><div><strong>wie hoch</strong> This phrase literally translates to "how high" in English. In this context, it’s an idiomatic expression used to ask about the amount or level of something, similar to saying "how much" or "what is the amount".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state or existence of something.</div><div><strong>mein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "my" in English. It shows ownership, indicating that something belongs to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Saldo</strong> This is a German noun meaning "balance". It refers to the amount of balance, for instance, in a bank account.</div><div><strong>jetzt</strong> This means "now" in English. It’s used here to ask for the current state or amount of something, in this case, the account balance.</div>','<h2>Jetzt nimmst du die rechte Fahrbahn.</h2><div><strong>Jetzt</strong> This is the German adverb for "now". It indicates the current time or moment when the action is taking place.</div><div><strong>nimmst</strong> This comes from the German verb "nehmen", which means "to take". "Nimmst" is the second-person singular present tense form, combined with "du" (you) as the subject.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This is the definite article in German for feminine and plural nouns in the nominative and accusative cases. Here, it precedes a feminine noun in the accusative case.</div><div><strong>rechte</strong> This is the German adjective for "right" in the feminine singular accusative form, referring to the right side or direction. It refers to the correct driving path.</div><div><strong>Fahrbahn</strong> This is a German noun meaning "lane" or "carriageway". It is a feminine noun in the singular accusative case, referring to the specific part of the road to be taken.</div>','<h2>Jetzt kannst du deinen Nachtisch essen.</h2><div><strong>Jetzt</strong> This is the German adverb for "now". It indicates the current moment or the immediate future.</div><div><strong>kannst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "können", which means "to be able to" or "can". Here, it gives the listener the permission or ability to do something.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>deinen</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "dein" in the accusative masculine singular form, meaning "your". It indicates possession of the noun that follows, which is "Nachtisch", and changes to "deinen" to agree with the gender, number, and case of the noun it refers to.</div><div><strong>Nachtisch</strong> This is a German noun for "dessert". In this sentence, it is in the accusative case as it is the direct object of the verb "essen".</div><div><strong>essen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb meaning "to eat". In this sentence structure, it is used after the modal verb "können" to indicate what action the subject is able to do, which is to eat in this context.</div>','<h2>Nein, ich bin geschieden, und jetzt ledig...</h2><div><strong>Nein</strong> This is the German word for "no". It negates a statement or responds negatively to a question.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>bin</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>geschieden</strong> This is a past participle used as an adjective in German, meaning "divorced". It indicates that the person has completed the process of legal separation from a spouse.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>jetzt</strong> This is the German adverb for "now". It indicates the current moment or a recent change in the state of affairs.</div><div><strong>ledig</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "single". It describes a person who is not married or in a civil partnership and can also imply that the person is unmarried after a divorce or separation.</div>','<h2>Ihr könnt jetzt die Kerzen ausblasen.</h2><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>könnt</strong> This is the second-person plural present tense form of the modal verb "können", which means "can" or "to be able to". It expresses ability or permission.</div><div><strong>jetzt</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "now". It specifies the time when the action is to take place.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This is the definite article in German for feminine or plural nouns in the accusative case. Here, it precedes the plural noun "Kerzen".</div><div><strong>Kerzen</strong> This is the plural form of the German noun "Kerze", which means "candles".</div><div><strong>ausblasen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb that means "to blow out". In this sentence, it represents the action being directed at the candles.</div>','<h2>Nein, es gibt immer Platz.</h2><div><strong>Nein</strong> This is the German word for "no". It is used to negate a statement or respond negatively to a question.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s used here as a dummy subject in this impersonal construction.</div><div><strong>gibt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "geben", which means "to give" or "there is/are" in this context. It’s stating the existence or availability of something.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "always". It indicates that something is perpetually true or constant.</div><div><strong>Platz</strong> This is a German noun meaning "space" or "room". It’s used here to indicate that there’s always room or space available. In German, nouns are capitalized, and "Platz" is in the nominative case here, being the thing that exists.</div>','<h2>Sie sind immer glücklich.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German pronoun for "they" when capitalized, or "you" in the formal singular or plural. It’s the subject of the sentence and determines the verb form.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense, or formal singular/plural second-person present tense, of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being of the subject in this context.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "always". It describes the frequency of the state of being expressed by the verb "sind".</div><div><strong>glücklich</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "happy". It describes the mood of the subject "Sie". When used as a predicate adjective as in this sentence, it is not inflected for case, gender, or number.</div>','<h2>Ich verliere immer meine Schlüssel.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>verliere</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "verlieren", which means "to lose". It shows the action that the subject is performing.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This word translates to "always" in English. It is an adverb describing the frequency with which the subject loses something.</div><div><strong>meine</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in the first-person singular, and its form changes according to the gender of the noun it describes. In this case, "meine" indicates that the subjects being referred to, the keys, are owned by the speaker.</div><div><strong>Schlüssel</strong> This is the German word for "keys". It is the direct object of the sentence, meaning it’s what is being lost by the subject.</div>','<h2>Du sagst immer lustige Sachen.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It is informal and used to address a single person that the speaker knows well. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>sagst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "sagen", which means "to say" or "to tell". It indicates what the subject is doing.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This translates to "always" in English. It’s an adverb that describes the frequency at which the action takes place.</div><div><strong>lustige</strong> This is the accusative plural form of the adjective "lustig", which means "funny" in English. It describes the noun that follows and must agree in case, number, and gender.</div><div><strong>Sachen</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Sache", which means "thing" or "things". In this context, it translates to "things" as in "You always say funny things". It’s in the accusative case because it’s the direct object of the verb "sagst".</div>','<h2>Er arbeitet immer stehend.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>arbeitet</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "arbeiten", which means "to work". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "always". It describes the frequency with which the subject performs the action.</div><div><strong>stehend</strong> This is a German adverb or participle that means "standing". It describes the manner in which the subject is working. In this case, it implies that he is standing while he works, as opposed to sitting or being in some other position.</div>','<h2>Die Mädchen gewannen immer.</h2><div><strong>Die</strong> This is the definite article in German for plural nouns, and it’s used here to specify "the" girls.</div><div><strong>Mädchen</strong> This is a neutral noun meaning "girls" in German. Despite referring to females, the noun itself is not feminine but neutral (das Mädchen), and it takes the plural form without adding an "n" or "en" which is common for most plural nouns in German.</div><div><strong>gewannen</strong> This is the third-person plural past tense form of the verb "gewinnen", which means "to win". It indicates that the action of winning was done by the girls and it’s in the past tense.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is an adverb meaning "always" in English. It denotes that the action of winning happened consistently or every time.</div>','<h2>Ich habe immer eine Katze gewollt.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have". It is used here to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This word means "always" in English. It indicates that the action or desire has been consistent over a period of time.</div><div><strong>eine</strong> This is the indefinite article for feminine and neuter nouns in the nominative and accusative cases in German, equivalent to "a" in English.</div><div><strong>Katze</strong> This is a feminine noun in German, which means "cat"</div><div><strong>gewollt</strong> This is the past participle of the modal verb "wollen", which means "to want". Combined with the auxiliary verb "haben", it forms the present perfect tense, indicating a past desire or wish.</div>','<h2>Er fällt immer aus der Hängematte.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is a German pronoun for "he". It is the third-person singular subject pronoun and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fällt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "fallen", which means "to fall". It suggests that the action is taking place in the present and is done by the subject "he".</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "always". It indicates that the action of falling happens consistently or repeatedly.</div><div><strong>aus</strong> This is a German preposition meaning "out of". In this sentence, it is used together with "der" as part of a prepositional phrase to indicate the starting point of the motion.</div><div><strong>der</strong> This is the definite article "the" in German and is the masculine/dative singular form. Here, it accompanies the noun "Hängematte" forming a prepositional phrase with "aus" to specify the object he is falling out of.</div><div><strong>Hängematte</strong> This is a German noun meaning "hammock". It is the object from which "he" falls out, and it’s in the dative case because of the preposition "aus" which requires the dative when it indicates a place from where something moves away.</div>','<h2>Du denkst immer über ihn nach.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing someone informally.</div><div><strong>denkst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "denken", which means "to think". It indicates that the subject "Du" is performing the action of thinking.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is an adverb meaning "always" in English. It describes the frequency with which the action of thinking is performed.</div><div><strong>über</strong> This is a preposition which, in this context, means "about". It is used to introduce the object of thought.</div><div><strong>ihn</strong> This is the third-person singular masculine pronoun in German, equivalent to "him" in English. It serves as the object of the preposition "über", indicating that the thought is directed toward a male individual.</div><div><strong>nach</strong> This word can have various meanings, but in this sentence, it is a part of the separable verb "nachdenken" which means "to think about" or "to contemplate". When constructing a sentence with a separable verb in German, the prefix (in this case, "nach-") is separated and placed at the end of the clause.</div>','<h2>Über wen spricht Niklas immer?</h2><div><strong>Über</strong> This is a German preposition which means "about" in English. It is used to indicate the topic or person being discussed or spoken about.</div><div><strong>wen</strong> This is the accusative case of the interrogative pronoun "wer" in German, which means "who" in English. "Wen" is used instead of "wer" when asking about the direct object of the verb, in this case, the person Niklas is always talking about.</div><div><strong>spricht</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sprechen", which means "to speak" or "to talk" in English. It indicates the action being performed by the subject (Niklas).</div><div><strong>Niklas</strong> This is a proper noun, a German male first name. In this sentence, Niklas is the subject, the person who is talking.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "always". It is used here to indicate the frequency of the action, suggesting that Niklas talks about the person in question habitually or consistently.</div>','<h2>Oh Anna! Du erfindest immer Geschichten!</h2><div><strong>Oh</strong> This is an interjection in German, used to express a range of emotions like surprise, pain, sadness, or in this case, possibly exasperation. It is the same as "oh" in English.</div><div><strong>Anna</strong> This is a proper noun, a female given name. In this sentence, it is the person being addressed directly, hence the use of the exclamation mark after it.</div><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>erfindest</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "erfinden", which means "to invent" or "to make up". In this sentence, "du erfindest" translates to "you invent" or "you make up".</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "always" or "every time". It’s used to indicate that the action is done repeatedly or habitually.</div><div><strong>Geschichten</strong> This is a plural noun meaning "stories" or "tales". This is the direct object in the sentence, indicating what is being invented/made up by the subject.</div>','<h2>Du bist immer fröhlich, wenn du aufwachst.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>bist</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "always". It’s used here to describe the frequency with which the subject is happy.</div><div><strong>fröhlich</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "cheerful" or "happy". It describes the subject’s mood or state.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a German subordinating conjunction meaning "whenever" or "when". It introduces a dependent clause in the sentence.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is repeated as the second-person singular pronoun in German, referring to the same person as before. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>aufwachst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "aufwachen", which means "to wake up". It describes the action taken by the subject in the subordinate clause.</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);